//
//   Part 1: FormulationCatalog (5 results)
//     F1-F5: Admissibility status unchanged by complexification
//
//   Part 2: ImaginaryTimeEntry (3 results)
//     E1-E3: Entry point varies (fiber artifact), mass reduction constant (physical)
//
//   Part 3: LinearizedSectorAnalysis (4 results)
//     L1-L4: Mass reduction is linearized, admissible, testable
//
//   Part 4: ExtendedFormulationFiber (3 results)
//     FIB1-FIB3: Fiber extends with new artifact properties
//
//   Part 5: Comparison Table (1 result)
//     TAB1: Full 5-formulation comparison with complex time
//
//   Part 6: TEGRDeepDive (3 results)
//     TEGR1-TEGR3: Torsion complex, scalar has im part, projection phenomenon
//
//   Part 7: Spin2Analysis (3 results)  [Note: example names use S2 prefix]
//     S2-1 to S2-3: Background complex, Isaacson has im terms, fully admissible
//
// KEY FINDINGS:
//   1. Complexification preserves admissibility: no formulation changes status
//   2. Every formulation acquires imaginary-time contributions
//   3. WHERE the contribution enters is a fiber artifact (K vs Q vs background)
//   4. The mass reduction Δm is constant across the fiber: PHYSICAL
//   5. The effect is linearized: lives in the admissible, evidence-rich sector
//   6. TEGR is the critical case: imaginary-time enters through Q (projection)
//   7. Spin-2 free is fully admissible and still predicts the effect
